			<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="comment-4519">
			<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/f493479bdffdb4eb5564f22f7b0f9789?s=32&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D32&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-32 photo' height='32' width='32' />			<cite>CMeier</cite> Says:						<br />

			<small class="commentmetadata"><a href="#comment-4519" title="">November 21, 2013 at 8:58 am</a> </small>

			<p>Healthcare.gov is *not* that complicated. The guts are basically 1) a simple web front end that stores a small set of per user info, 2) a rules engine that combines fairly static data about available plans with the particular data stored in 1 to provide cost data to the users, and 3) a messaging system that sends the data from 1 to the external insurance companies once the user has made their choice based on the results returned by 2. Toss in reporting and an interface for the insurance cos to manage the semi-static rules data and you are done.</p>
<p>It could have been done by a competent team of less than 25 pms/business analysts/devs/testers in two and half years for under $25 million total including hardware and personnel costs. Where did they spend a half a billion dollars?</p>
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
